description:
#wahhabism #islam #muslimskeptic 

This in-depth documentary presents the history of Wahhabism as a political religious movement, its break from traditional Sunni Islam, and its evolution into the 20th century. Daniel Haqiqatjou cites over 60 historical quotations from Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab and the main figures of Wahhabism. Also cited are the Sunni scholars throughout history who have critiqued Ibn Abd al-Wahhab and described the core doctrine of Wahhabism as a revival of the oldest heresy in Islam: Kharijism.

The documentary problematizes the Wahhabi claim that it is the purest expression of Islamic monotheism and that it is the faithful preservation of the creed (aqida) of the Salaf, Ahmad ibn Hanbal, and Ibn Taymiyya. The documentary demonstrates that Wahhabism's focus on a claimed purity of aqida has been used -- from the beginning until today -- as a political tool to generate hatred against non-Wahhabi Muslims and spark violent jihad against them.

55:52 ...
Question: Does Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab excuse people due to ignorance?

Answer:

Shaykh Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab – may Allah have mercy on him – did excuse ignorance in matters of shirk (polytheism) and kufr (disbelief), as long as the evidence (ḥujjah) had not been established against the person. This is clearly stated in his books and letters.

His explicit statements about excusing ignorance:

1. He said in ad-Durar as-Saniyyah (10/132):



> “As for takfir, I only declare a person to be a disbeliever if he knows the religion of the Messenger and then, after knowing it, he reviles it, prohibits people from following it, and shows enmity towards those who practice it. Such a person is the one I consider a disbeliever.”



— Meaning: He does not declare the ignorant person a disbeliever — only the one who knowingly opposes the truth after evidence has reached him.

2. He also said (ad-Durar as-Saniyyah 10/51):



> “As for the lies and slanders they accuse us of — such as that we declare people disbelievers in general, that we oblige hijrah (migration) to us from those who can manifest their religion, or that we declare disbelievers those who do not excommunicate others or do not fight — all of this is false and slanderous, used to turn people away from the religion of Allah and His Messenger.”



3. In a letter to one of his opponents, he wrote:



> “As for takfir, I say: Whoever commits shirk out of ignorance and the proof has not reached him — then he is excused.”



Did he contradict this in some places?

At times, strong statements are quoted from him, but when examined in context, it's clear that he was referring to:

People upon whom the evidence had been clearly established.

Or those living in Muslim lands where knowledge was widespread and ignorance was no longer an excuse.

Or individuals who persisted in shirk after the truth had been made clear.


Conclusion:

Yes, Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab did excuse ignorance in matters of shirk and kufr, as long as the evidence had not reached the individual.
He only declared someone a disbeliever when the proof had been conveyed, understood, and then deliberately rejected.

comments.text:
⁠ @figuraclass444 

Ashʿarī, Māturīdī, and Hanbalī are the theological schools that represent the understanding of the Salaf. These are the three recognized schools of ʿAqīdah (creed) within Ahl al-Sunnah wa al-Jamāʿah. If you’ve been misinformed about this, I can only convey the truth to you—it’s up to you to verify and investigate who these scholars truly were.

In matters of Fiqh, the four established schools—Ḥanafī, Mālikī, Shāfiʿī, and Ḥanbalī—all have authenticated chains of transmission back to the Prophet ﷺ. These schools didn’t simply transmit hadith—they preserved and transmitted the understanding of those hadiths based on the methodology of the early generations.

You cannot build your religion on isolated or cherry-picked statements from the Salaf. True adherence means following the schools that preserved not only the words but also the interpretive framework of the Salaf. That’s the whole point of having a school of thought: it’s not just the sources, but how they were understood and applied.

I recommend you read:
	•	“Ar-Radd ʿalā Man Ittabaʿa Ghayr al-Madhāhib al-Arbaʿa” (The Response to Those Who Follow Other than the Four Madhhabs) by Imām Ibn Rajab al-Ḥanbalī.

And also:
	•	“Al-ʿIlal” by Imām ʿAlī ibn al-Madīnī, a major authority in hadith and the teacher of Imām al-Bukhārī. In his work, you’ll see how the four schools trace their methodology and rulings back to the Messenger ﷺ, with clear chains of transmission.

Brother, I’m sharing this with you out of care and sincerity. It’s important to seek guidance from scholars who respect and speak on behalf of these schools, not those who dismiss the insights of Imāms like Mālik, as if he didn’t know the hadith or its correct application. Remember, these schools are not the opinion of just one scholar—they are the result of generations of scholarship rooted in revelation and transmitted with precision. Look at scholars and how they attribute themselves to these schools saying: imam So & So Almaliki, Alhanafi, Ashafi’i, Alhanbali…….

Please forgive my English—it’s not my first language. 

I asked ChatGPT to make it better 😅

On the authority of Ibn ʿAbbās (رضى الله عنه):

اللهم بارك لنا في شامنا ويمننا. فقال رجل من القوم يا نبي الله وفي عراقنا . قال : إن بها قرن الشيطان

“O Allāh! Bless our Shām and our Yemen. A man from the people said, “O Messenger of Allāh! And our ‘Iraq?” He said, “Indeed there is the horn of the devil….” [At-Tabarani 1204]
